      "content": "I understand your concern with memory usage. To optimize the loop while using the standard CSV module, consider processing the file in chunks. This way, you can handle one chunk at a time, reducing the memory footprint. Here's an example of how you can do that:\n\n```python\nimport csv\n\nchunk_size = 10000  # Adjust the chunk size based on your machine's memory\nwith open('your_file.csv', mode='r') as file:\n    csv_reader = csv.reader(file)\n    header = next(csv_reader)  # Skip the header row\n\n    for i, row in enumerate(csv_reader):\n        if i % chunk_size == 0:\n            print(f\"Processing chunk {i // chunk_size + 1}\")\n        # Process the row here\n        # ...\n\n# Continue with any additional processing after the loop\n```\n\nBy processing the file in chunks, you can keep the memory usage under control while still being able to process large CSV files efficiently. Remember to adjust the `chunk_size` based on your machine's memory capacity. If you need further assistance, feel free to ask.",
